[1]
Date: Sat 9 Aug 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Canoe.com, Sat 9 Aug 2003 2003 [edited]
<http://www.canoe.ca/NationalTicker/CANOE-wire.West-Nile-Virus.html>

Canada: First "Autochthonous" Case of West Nile Virus Infection in Ontario
--------------------------------------------------
An elderly person in Ottawa has tested positive for West Nile virus, health
officials said on Fri 8 Aug 2003, the second confirmed case in Canada this
summer.
An investigation is underway to determine where the patient, who is being
treated in hospital, was infected. The only other confirmed case of West
Nile was found in Saskatchewan in July 2003. Another Ontario resident, from
Renfrew County near Ottawa, is believed to have contracted the virus while
visiting the United States in July, but is still deemed a probable case by
Health Canada.
"Although the first case reported in Ontario in late July was acquired
during travel outside the province, this new case underscores more than
ever our need to remain vigilant in using personal protective measures
against this virus," Colin D'Cunha, Ontario's commissioner of public
health, said in a release. John Letherby, a spokesman for the Ontario
Ministry of Health, said that while officials are glad to see the number of
cases this summer is down dramatically compared with 2002, every new
infection is a concern.
There were 416 probable or confirmed cases of West Nile virus in Canada
during 2002. But officials think that was likely just a fraction of the
actual number, since it's believed 80 percent of people who get the virus
have such mild symptoms they aren't even aware they've been infected. Only
Ontario and Quebec recorded cases of the virus, the first year there were
human cases in Canada. There were 20 deaths attributed to West Nile: 18 in
Ontario and 2 in Quebec.
The number of West Nile cases in the United States has tripled since last
week and will likely top 2002's record total, according to American health
officials. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that at
least 182 people in 17 states are infected. At least 5 deaths have been
attributed to the virus so far in 2003. In 2002, 4156 people in the U.S.
caught the virus, and 284 died.
To date, 283 dead birds have tested positive for West Nile virus in Canada,
with Manitoba (93) and Ontario (81) reporting most of the cases. Dead birds
have also tested positive for the virus in Saskatchewan (53), Quebec (33),
Alberta (22), and New Brunswick (one). Saskatchewan confirmed Canada's
first domestic case of West Nile virus in a human this year on 25 Jul 2003,
the first time someone had contracted the virus in the province. Provincial
health officials said the man was from Assiniboia, 130 kilometres southwest
of Regina.
******
[2]
Date: Sun 10 Aug 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada, West Nile Virus Surveillance, Thu 7 Aug 2003 [edited]
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/wnv-vwn/mon_e.html>

West Nile Virus Surveillance Data as of Thu 7 Aug 2003
-------------------------------------------------------
Human
-----
One confirmed case in Saskatchewan; West Nile virus detected in blood
donation [see: West Nile virus, blood donor - Canada (Saskatchewan)
20030726.1842]. One suspected case in Ontario (possibly contracted in the USA).
Equines
-------
7 confirmed equine cases; Ontario (1), Manitoba (2), Saskatchewan (1),
Alberta (3).
Mosquitoes
----------
The Ministry of Health and Long-Term Care (MOHLTC) has been advised that as
of Tue 15 Jul 2003 the report of one West Nile virus positive mosquito pool
(in Ontario), which was posted on 24 Jun 2003 is incorrect. The sample
taken 18 Jun 2003 which was tested by a private laboratory, upon further
confirmatory testing, has proven negative for West Nile virus.
As of 7 Aug 2003, six pools of mosquitoes have tested positive; Quebec (1),
Ontario (2), Manitoba (1), Alberta (3).
Wild Birds
----------
Test Results by Province:
Province/No. submitted for testing/No.tested/No. confirmed positive/
